  "topic_name": "Heat and Temperature",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Heat is a form of energy that flows from hot to cold objects. Temperature measures how hot or cold something is. A thermometer measures temperature in Celsius (0C = freezing, 100C = boiling water). Heat transfers by: conduction (through solids, particles pass heat), convection (through fluids, hot rises, cold sinks), and radiation (without medium, like Sun's heat). Conductors like metals allow heat to pass easily. Insulators like wood, plastic, rubber do not. Heat causes materials to expand; cooling causes contraction.",
    "rules": [
      "Heat: a form of energy",
      "Temperature: measure of hotness or coldness",
      "Heat flows from hot to cold",
      "Thermometer measures temperature",
      "Celsius scale: 0C = freezing, 100C = boiling",
      "Conduction: heat through solids",
      "Convection: heat through fluids",
      "Radiation: heat without medium",
      "Conductors: metals allow heat flow",
      "Insulators: wood, plastic, rubber block heat",
      "Heat causes expansion, cold causes contraction"
    ]
  },
